Step-by-step: GitHub Actions + Docker Hub pipeline
✅ Step 1 – Prepare your Python project

Your repo should look like this:

python-app/
│── app.py
│── requirements.txt
│── Dockerfile
Example Dockerfile
FROM python:3.10-slim

WORKDIR /app

COPY . .
RUN pip install -r requirements.txt

CMD ["python", "app.py"]
✅ Step 2 – Push project to GitHub
git init
git add .
git commit -m "Initial commit"
git branch -M main
git remote add origin https://github.com/<your-username>/python-app.git
git push -u origin main
🔐 Step 3 – Add Docker Hub credentials (VERY IMPORTANT)

Go to your repo →
Settings → Secrets and variables → Actions → New repository secret

Add:

DOCKER_USERNAME → your Docker Hub username
DOCKER_PASSWORD → your Docker Hub access token (not your password)

👉 Create token from Docker Hub:

Account Settings → Security → Access Tokens
📁 Step 4 – Create GitHub Actions workflow

Create this file in your repo:

.github/workflows/build-push.yml

Paste your YAML:

name: Docker Build & Push

on:
  push:
    branches: [ main ]
  pull_request:
    branches: [ main ]

jobs:
  docker:
    runs-on: ubuntu-latest

    steps:
      - uses: actions/checkout@v3

      - name: Set up Docker Buildx
        uses: docker/setup-buildx-action@v3

      - name: Login to Docker Hub
        uses: docker/login-action@v3
        with:
          username: ${{ secrets.DOCKER_USERNAME }}
          password: ${{ secrets.DOCKER_PASSWORD }}

      - name: Build and push
        uses: docker/build-push-action@v5
        with:
          context: .
          push: true
          tags: ${{ secrets.DOCKER_USERNAME }}/python-app:latest
🚀 Step 5 – Trigger the pipeline

Just push any change:

git add .
git commit -m "Trigger CI"
git push
🔍 Step 6 – Watch pipeline run

Go to:
👉 GitHub repo → Actions tab

You’ll see:

Build starting
Docker image building
Image pushed to Docker Hub
📦 Step 7 – Verify Docker image

Go to your Docker Hub repo:

https://hub.docker.com/r/<your-username>/python-app

Pull it locally:

docker pull <your-username>/python-app:latest

Run it:

docker run -p 5000:5000 <your-username>/python-app
💡 What’s happening behind the scenes
GitHub detects a push
Workflow runs on a cloud VM
Docker image is built using Buildx
Image is pushed to Docker Hub automatically
⚠️ Common mistakes (very important)
❌ Wrong Docker credentials → login fails
❌ Repo name mismatch → image not found
❌ No Dockerfile → build fails
❌ Using password instead of token → authentication error
✅ Bonus (Best Practice Upgrade)

If you want versioning:

tags: |
  ${{ secrets.DOCKER_USERNAME }}/python-app:latest
  ${{ secrets.DOCKER_USERNAME }}/python-app:${{ github.sha }}
